1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,705
Let's take a look at a demo on how to set up your range programmatically,

2
00:00:03,705 --> 00:00:06,400
identify outliers and remove them using Pandas,

3
00:00:06,400 --> 00:00:09,390
and finally, we will see the impact on summary statistics.

4
00:00:09,390 --> 00:00:14,760
We start by importing pandas and reading in our data set into a DataFrame.

5
00:00:14,760 --> 00:00:17,505
Next, we're going to use the.describe function.

6
00:00:17,505 --> 00:00:19,815
With this dataset, we have two columns,

7
00:00:19,815 --> 00:00:21,210
student ID, and age,

8
00:00:21,210 --> 00:00:23,430
corresponding to middle and high-school students,

9
00:00:23,430 --> 00:00:26,925
which means our age range is about 11-18.

10
00:00:26,925 --> 00:00:29,865
The dataset has 527 rows.

11
00:00:29,865 --> 00:00:33,950
Now, let's focus on the age column for the outlier detection for this demo.

12
00:00:33,950 --> 00:00:36,170
From the results of.describe,

13
00:00:36,170 --> 00:00:41,330
we immediately see the minimum value for the age column is three and the max is 75,

14
00:00:41,330 --> 00:00:45,200
which is clearly out of our age range of 11-18.

15
00:00:45,200 --> 00:00:48,930
Applying the sort values method,

16
00:00:49,600 --> 00:00:54,590
we can actually start to see that there are many values below

17
00:00:54,590 --> 00:00:58,955
11 and above 18 as part of our age column in this dataset.

18
00:00:58,955 --> 00:01:02,460
Let's go through how to manually create a range for identifying the outliers.

19
00:01:02,460 --> 00:01:06,590
In this case, since we know that the range of ages should be 11-18.

20
00:01:06,590 --> 00:01:11,885
What we can do is go ahead and use indexing to get the list of rows violating our range.

21
00:01:11,885 --> 00:01:15,200
We can use df.loc to access the rows and

22
00:01:15,200 --> 00:01:19,370
specify our conditions as values and the age column being less than 18,

23
00:01:19,370 --> 00:01:22,310
where we can see here there's a small number of outliers.

24
00:01:22,310 --> 00:01:25,625
We can also do the same thing for ages greater than 18,

25
00:01:25,625 --> 00:01:29,875
where we can see there's a larger number of outliers present in the DataFrame.

26
00:01:29,875 --> 00:01:34,280
What if we didn't know this age range should be 11-18?

27
00:01:34,280 --> 00:01:38,570
Let's use standard deviation to figure out our upper and lower outlier boundaries.

28
00:01:38,570 --> 00:01:40,580
We're going to pull the information we need for

29
00:01:40,580 --> 00:01:42,815
the calculation from the.describe function.

30
00:01:42,815 --> 00:01:45,410
Again,.describe as returning a DataFrame,

31
00:01:45,410 --> 00:01:50,730
so we can actually access the mean and standard deviation values from it using.loc.

32
00:01:50,960 --> 00:01:53,525
Now, to calculate the upper bound,

33
00:01:53,525 --> 00:01:56,915
I'm using here the mean plus 1 standard deviation.

34
00:01:56,915 --> 00:02:00,755
For the lower bound, I'm using the mean minus 1 standard deviation.

35
00:02:00,755 --> 00:02:04,685
Notice how here, if we print the values of the upper and lower bound,

36
00:02:04,685 --> 00:02:08,045
since we're assuming we don't know the actual age range,

37
00:02:08,045 --> 00:02:11,390
the upper and lower bound values are slightly off.

38
00:02:11,390 --> 00:02:13,100
The upper bound is about 25,

39
00:02:13,100 --> 00:02:15,560
and the lower bound is about seven.

40
00:02:15,560 --> 00:02:18,170
Again, we can retrieve the rows that are

41
00:02:18,170 --> 00:02:21,320
violating or outside of this boundary using indexing.

42
00:02:21,320 --> 00:02:26,150
Note here how we're using the OR operator or the OR Boolean operator

43
00:02:26,150 --> 00:02:31,445
so we can get rows both below the lower bound and above the upper bound at the same time.

44
00:02:31,445 --> 00:02:34,765
Let's run this to get a list of these violating rows.

45
00:02:34,765 --> 00:02:36,605
To drop these outliers,

46
00:02:36,605 --> 00:02:39,755
we need to first get the index of the outlier rows that meet

47
00:02:39,755 --> 00:02:43,300
or just identifying here and then pass it to Pandas drop function.

48
00:02:43,300 --> 00:02:44,740
Let's take a look at how to do this.

49
00:02:44,740 --> 00:02:48,480
Here, we're getting the index of these rows.

50
00:02:48,530 --> 00:02:53,420
Then next we're going ahead and passing them to Pandas.drop function,

51
00:02:53,420 --> 00:02:56,270
specifying the index parameter as the index of

52
00:02:56,270 --> 00:02:59,870
the violating rows and then assigning this to a new variable newdf.

53
00:02:59,870 --> 00:03:01,895
If we run.describe on this,

54
00:03:01,895 --> 00:03:03,260
we can start to see that

55
00:03:03,260 --> 00:03:08,105
our min value is at 10 after dropping the rows and the max is at 17.

56
00:03:08,105 --> 00:03:09,800
The mean is about 14,

57
00:03:09,800 --> 00:03:13,355
and the standard deviation at approximately two, whereas previously,

58
00:03:13,355 --> 00:03:15,185
if we look at our original DataFrame,

59
00:03:15,185 --> 00:03:21,020
we can see that the mean was about 16 and the standard deviation was about nine.

60
00:03:21,020 --> 00:03:23,330
We can see the dramatic and obvious influence

61
00:03:23,330 --> 00:03:26,770
our outliers had on this standard deviation calculation.

62
00:03:26,770 --> 00:03:30,575
I'd like to revisit one last thing on pandas drop function.

63
00:03:30,575 --> 00:03:35,680
Note how we directly assign the result of the drop function to newdf.

64
00:03:35,680 --> 00:03:40,430
If we specified a argument called in-place equals true when doing the drop,

65
00:03:40,430 --> 00:03:44,945
it would automatically overwrite the values in our original DataFrame df.

66
00:03:44,945 --> 00:03:47,245
We wouldn't even need to assign it to a value.

67
00:03:47,245 --> 00:03:50,270
Let's do that here, where we specify the dark drop function and

68
00:03:50,270 --> 00:03:54,230
the index and have in place equal to true without assigning it to a variable.

69
00:03:54,230 --> 00:03:55,790
As you can see here,

70
00:03:55,790 --> 00:03:58,910
the results from describe on this df variable,

71
00:03:58,910 --> 00:04:00,230
which is the original DataFrame,

72
00:04:00,230 --> 00:04:04,760
are now the same as what we got as part of our newdf variable.

73
00:04:04,760 --> 00:04:07,130
While in-place equals true can simplify

74
00:04:07,130 --> 00:04:09,740
your implementation because it allows you to minimize the amount

75
00:04:09,740 --> 00:04:14,485
of new variables you create and just directly replace values in your original DataFrame,

76
00:04:14,485 --> 00:04:18,215
it can be dangerous because it overwrites your original data.

77
00:04:18,215 --> 00:04:21,390
Be cautious and frugal with its use.

